</span></span>

</p/><p><strong>Summary: </strong>
I’m hosting the August Emacs Blog Carnival.
</p>
        <p>We’re onto month three of the <a href="https://www.emacswiki.org/emacs/Carnival">Emacs Carnival</a> and I’m hosting <time datetime="2025-08" title="2025-08">August</time> with the
topic of “Your Elevator Pitch for Emacs.”</p>
<p>Those of us using <span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emacs">Emacs</a></span> <small><a class="ref" rel="tag opener" aria-label="Other site-wide references of “Emacs”" title="Other site-wide references of “Emacs”" href="https://takeonrules.com/site-map/glossary/#abbr-dfn-GLOSSARY-EMACS">&#128214;</a></small>
 have likely internalized many reasons for why we chose
and keep choosing <span>Emacs</span>
.  However, in an era of a rising sea of digital slop,
I’d love to read of people making a case for why one might invest time and
energy in adopting or continuing to use <span>Emacs</span>
.</p>
<p>And maybe that elevator is a quick one floor shift, only a blurb before the
doors open; or you’re stuck in that elevator with a captive audience while the
maintenance crew ambles their way to get you all out.  It’s your elevator and
your editor, get pitching!</p>
